==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|meticulōsus||full of fear, timid, fearful, terrible, frightful}}, from {{m|la|metus||fear}} and {{m|la|-culōsus}}, extracted from {{m|la|perīculōsus||perilous}}. Sense of "characterized by very precise, conscientious attention to details" is from {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|méticuleux}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/mɨˈtɪkjɨlɨs/|/mɨˈtɪkjuləs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-uk-meticulous.ogg|Audio (UK)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪkjələs|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{label|en|archaic}} [[timid|Timid]], [[fearful]], overly [[cautious]].
# Characterized by very [[precise]], [[conscientious]] [[attention]] to [[detail]]s.
#* {{quote-book|year=1943|author={{w|Franklin D. Roosevelt}}|title=[[S:Roosevelt's Fireside Chat, 28 July 1943|Roosevelt's Fireside Chat, 28 July 1943]]
|passage=The '''meticulous''' care with which the operation in Sicily was planned has paid dividends. Our casualties in men, in ships and materiel have been low—in fact, far below our estimate.}}

